Method Detail

conjugate

public static Complex conjugate(Complex c)
Finds the conjugate of the given Complex.

The conjugate of any Complex represented as "a + bi" is given as "a - bi".

Parameters:
c - the Complex whose conjugate is to be found.
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the conjugate of c

reciprocal

public static Complex reciprocal(Complex c)
Finds the reciprocal of the given Complex.

The reciprocal of any Complex represented as "a + bi" is given as "1 / (a + bi)".

Parameters:
c - the Complex whose reciprocal is to be found.
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the reciprocal of c

add

public static Complex add(Complex c1,
                          Complex c2)
Finds the sum of the given Complexes.

The sum of any two Complexes "a + bi" and "x + yi" will always be equal to "(a+x) + (b+y)i".

Parameters:
c1 - the first Complex
c2 - the second Complex
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the sum of c1 and c2

add

public static Complex add(Complex c,
                          double num)
Finds the sum of the given Complex and a non-complex number.

The sum of any Complex ("a + bi") and any non-complex number ("x") will always be equal to "(a+x) + bi"

Parameters:
c - the Complex
num - the non-complex number
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the sum of c and num

subtract

public static Complex subtract(Complex c1,
                               Complex c2)
Finds the difference between two Complexes

The difference between any two Complexes will be the differences between their real and imaginary parts.

Parameters:
c1 - the first Complex
c2 - the second Complex
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the sum of c and num

subtract

public static Complex subtract(Complex c,
                               double num)
Finds the difference between the given Complex and a non-complex number.

The difference between any Complex and a non-complex number will always be the Complex's real value minus the number, with the imaginary value unchanged.

Parameters:
c - the Complex
num - the non-complex number
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the difference between c and num

multiply

public static Complex multiply(Complex c1,
                               Complex c2)
Finds the product of two Complexes.

If a Complex is multiplied by it's conjugate Complex, the resulting value will ALWAYS be real, with no imaginary part. Otherwise, the resulting product will likely contain an imaginary part.

Parameters:
c1 - the first Complex
c2 - the second Complex
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the product of c1 and c2

multiply

public static Complex multiply(Complex c,
                               double num)
Finds the product of a Complex and a non-complex number.

The product of a Complex and a non-complex number will always be the non-complex number distributed across the Complex's real and imaginary parts.

Parameters:
c - the Complex
num - the non-complex number
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the product of c and num

divide

public static Complex divide(Complex c1,
                             Complex c2)
Finds the quotient of two Complexes.

The quotient of two Complexes is always equal to the following: The multiplication of the first Complex and the conjugate of the second Complex, all divided by the the multiplication of the second Complex and it's conjugate.

Parameters:
c1 - the first Complex and the numerator
c2 - the second Complex and the denominator
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the quotient of c1 over c2

divide

public static Complex divide(Complex c,
                             double num)
Finds the quotient of a Complex and a non-complex number.

The quotient of a Complex and a non-complex number will always be the non-complex number distributed across the Complex's real and imaginary parts.

Parameters:
c - the Complex
num - the non-complex number
Returns:
a new Complex whose value is the quotient of c over num

mag

public static double mag(Complex c)
Finds the magnitude of a Complex number.

The magnitude (also known as the hypotenuse, rho, Z, etc) of any complex number is equal to the square root of the sum of the squares of the Complex's real and imaginary parts.

Parameters:
c - the Complex
Returns:
a double whose value is the magnitude (hypotenuse) of c
